ΤΗΕ only passage in this Satire from which its date can be conjectured is the allusion, in ll. 75-82‚ to the security of the port of Ostia, which probably refers to the improvement of that harbour by Trajan. The precise date of the enlargement of Ostia is unknown, but Pliny describes Trajan as ‘parens aedificandi' in the Panegyris 51, which refers to the early part of the reign. The parenthesis about the elephant, ll. 101-110, is in Juvenal's worst style. The last eight lines seem dragged in for· cibly, and have no meritos their own to plead as an excuse. On the other hand, the passages describing how Corvinus will be welcomed, ll. ¹-9 and 83-92‚ but especially the latter, are very charming.
